\begin_layout Itemize
Let us quickly recall the formulae for the determinant
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
that we learnt in high-school,
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 determinants:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
c & d
\end{array}\right|=ad-bc,
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
a & b & c\\
d & e & f\\
g & h & i
\end{array}\right|=aei-afh+bfg-bdi+cdh-ceg.
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To ensure we have understood 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:AxiomsForDeterminant"
plural "false"
caps "true"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

,
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
let us check that the three properties are satisfied 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
by our formula for the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 case.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Normalisation:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Clearly,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\begin{array}{cc}
1\\
 & 1
\end{array}\right|=1$
\end_inset

 (set 
\begin_inset Formula $b=c=0$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $ad$
\end_inset

 survives).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Similarly,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
1\\
 & 1\\
 &  & 1
\end{array}\right|=1$
\end_inset

 (set 
\begin_inset Formula $b=c=d=f=g=h=0$
\end_inset

;
 only the 
\begin_inset Formula $aei$
\end_inset

 term survives).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Antisymmetry:
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Clearly,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{vmatrix}1\\
 & 1
\end{vmatrix}=1$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{vmatrix} & 1\\
1
\end{vmatrix}=-1$
\end_inset

 (only 
\begin_inset Formula $-bc$
\end_inset

 survives).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Again,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
1\\
 & 1\\
 &  & 1
\end{array}\right|=1$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
1\\
 &  & 1\\
1
\end{array}\right|=1\cdot(-1)=-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Linearity in each row:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We leave this as a small exercise to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\begin{array}{cc}
a+a' & b+b'\\
c & d
\end{array}\right|\overset{\text{exercise}}{=}\left|\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
c & d
\end{array}\right|+\left|\begin{array}{cc}
a' & b'\\
c & d
\end{array}\right|.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is immediate
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\begin{array}{cc}
ta & tb\\
c & d
\end{array}\right|=t\left|\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
c & d
\end{array}\right|.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is worth pointing out that,
 in general,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(A+B)\neq\det(A)+\det(B)
\]

\end_inset

 and similarly,
 in general,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(tA)\neq t\det(A).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In fact,
 it turns out that if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(tA)=t^{n}\det(A).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Branch commentary
inverted 0
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Before we show that these three axioms uniquely specify the determinant function,
 we derive some interesting properties,
 assuming them (the three axioms).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\det:\F^{n\times n}\to\F$
\end_inset

 be as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:AxiomsForDeterminant"
plural "false"
caps "true"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

,
 satisfying the three axioms listed there.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\F^{n\times n}$
\end_inset

 be any .
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\det$
\end_inset

 also satisfies the following properties.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If any two rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are equal,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has a zero row,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Adding or subtracting a multiple of one row from another,
 leaves the determine unchanged.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

More generally,
 the determinant stays invariant,
 if one adds to a row,
 a linear combination of other rows (note,
 the remaining rows are left unchanged).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Branch proof
inverted 0
status open

\begin_layout Proof
Write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\text{---} & v_{1} & \text{---}\\
 & \vdots\\
\text{---} & v_{n} & \text{---}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and proceed as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
If any two rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are equal,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}=v_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det(A) & =\ \ \det(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{j}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots,\underbrace{v_{k}}_{k\text{th row}},\dots v_{n})\\
 & =-\det(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{k}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots,\underbrace{v_{j}}_{k\text{th row}},\dots v_{n}) & \text{By Axiom 2}\\
 & =-\det(A) & \because\text{ }v_{j}=v_{k}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and that in turn shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has a zero row,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}=(0\dots0)$
\end_inset

 is the all-zero row.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det(A) & =\det(v_{1},\dots,v_{k},\dots v_{n})\\
 & =\det(v_{1},\dots,0\cdot v_{k},\dots v_{n}) & \because\ 0\cdot v_{k}=v_{k}\\
 & =0\cdot\det(v_{1},\dots,v_{k},\dots v_{n}) & \text{By Axiom 3}\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
If the rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Without loss of generality,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}=\sum^{n}_{i=2}c_{i}v_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 One can therefore write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det(A) & =\det(v_{1},v_{2},\dots v_{n})\\
 & =\det\left(\sum^{n}_{i=2}c_{i}v_{i},v_{2},\dots v_{n}\right)\\
 & =\sum^{n}_{i=2}c_{i}\cdot\det(v_{i},v_{2},\dots v_{n}) & \text{By Axiom 3}\\
 & =\sum^{n}_{i=2}c_{i}\cdot0 & \text{From Property 1}\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Adding or subtracting a multiple of one row from another,
 leaves the determine unchanged.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(A)=\det(v_{1},\dots,v_{j},\dots v_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

Consider the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 which is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 except the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th row is replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}+cv_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\det(A') & =\det(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{j}+cv_{k}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots v_{n})\\
 & =\det(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{j}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots v_{n})+\\
 & \quad c\det(v_{1},\dots,\underbrace{v_{k}}_{j\text{th row}},\dots v_{n}) & \text{this term is zero from Property 1}\\
 & =\det(A).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
More generally,
 the determinant stays invariant,
 if one adds to a row,
 a linear combination of other rows (note,
 the remaining rows are left unchanged).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proceeding similarly,
 one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
 & v_{1}\\
 & \vdots\\
 & v_{k}+\sum_{i\neq j}c_{i}v_{i}\\
 & \vdots\\
 & v_{n}
\end{array}\right| & =\det\left(v_{1},\dots,v_{j}+\sum_{i\neq j}c_{i}v_{i},\dots v_{n}\right)\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\end_inset


\end_layout

